---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import { CITY_NAME } from 'astro:env/client';
---

<Base title="Privacy">
  <div class="max-w-2xl mx-auto p-4">
    <a href="/" class="btn btn-ghost btn-sm mb-4">&larr; Back to map</a>

    <div class="prose max-w-none">
      <h1>Privacy</h1>

      <p>
        {CITY_NAME} Cleanup Spots is a volunteer coordination tool. This page
        explains what data we collect, what we do with it, and what we don't do.
      </p>

      <h2>What we collect</h2>

      <h3>Email Addresses</h3>
      <p><strong>Email addresses</strong> are collected when you:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Report a new spot</li>
        <li>Add a task to a spot</li>
        <li>Claim a task</li>
        <li>Add a note to a spot</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        Emails are stored in our database but <strong>never displayed publicly</strong>.
        They are not visible on the map, in spot details, or in any API response.
        Only the site administrator can see them via direct database access.
      </p>
      <p>
        We do not send emails. We do not share email addresses with anyone.
        We do not use them for marketing or newsletters.
      </p>

      <h3>Volunteer names</h3>
      <p>
        When you claim a task, your name is displayed on the spot detail page
        so other volunteers can see who's working on it. This is visible to
        anyone who views the spot.
      </p>

      <h3>Location data</h3>
      <p>
        The "Near me" feature uses your browser's geolocation to center the map
        on your position. This data <strong>never leaves your browser</strong>.
        It is not sent to our server, not stored in our database, and not shared
        with anyone. Your browser will ask for permission before sharing your
        location.
      </p>

      <h3>Trip planning</h3>
      <p>
        When you add spots to your trip, the list is stored in your browser's
        local storage. This data stays on your device. It is not sent to our
        server. Clearing your browser data will remove it.
      </p>

      <h3>Map tiles</h3>
      <p>
        The map uses tiles from <a href="https://www.openstreetmap.org" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">OpenStreetMap</a>.
        When you view the map, your browser makes requests to OpenStreetMap's
        servers, which means they can see your IP address. This is standard for
        any website that displays a map. See
        <a href="https://wiki.osmfoundation.org/wiki/Privacy_Policy" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">OpenStreetMap's privacy policy</a>.
      </p>

      <h2>What we don't do</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>No cookies</li>
        <li>No analytics or tracking scripts</li>
        <li>No advertising</li>
        <li>No data sharing with third parties</li>
        <li>No user accounts or passwords</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Data retention</h2>
      <p>
        Spot, task, and volunteer data is stored indefinitely. There is currently
        no self-service way to delete your data. If you want your information
        removed, contact the site administrator.
      </p>

      <h2>Open source</h2>
      <p>
        This app is <a href="https://github.com/keenrodent/local-cleanup" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">open source</a>
        under the MIT license. You can read every line of code that handles
        your data.
      </p>

      <h2>Contact</h2>
      <p>
        Questions about privacy? Email <a href="mailto:k@knrhds.com">k@knrhds.com</a>.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</Base>
